  <content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p>I got interested in computers when my dad started bringing home a terminal to access his companies mainframe over a 300 baud telecoupled modem. The first terminals were paper-based, then we moved-on-up to a VT100. I got interested in programming because I wanted to be able to build my own game like <a href="http://www.rickadams.org/adventure/">Adventure</a> or <a href="http://www.infocom-if.org/downloads/downloads.html">Zork</a>. The rest as they say is history and some 20-25 years later I work for Microsoft. I never actually built an adventure game, but if I still wanted to, apparently <a href="http://neopoleon.com/blog">Rory</a> is <a href="http://neopoleon.com/blog/posts/15103.aspx">teaching a sesson</a> on <a href="http://www.inform-fiction.org">Inform</a> which apparently is a language for building Interactive Fiction. </p><p>Sounds like <a href="http://pacwest.ms/codecamp/pdx/1/">Code Camp</a> is going to be a blast. Note to self, bug Rory for his slides.</p>]]></content:encoded>
